<HEADLINE>
<P>
'BEST BUDDIES': GETTING INTO SPIRIT OF SPECIAL OLYMPICS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Anthony Shriver wanted to do something special for the Special Olympics and 
start his soap opera-addicted classmates at Georgetown University on the path 
to something more fulfilling. 
</P>
<P>
He did both by starting Best Buddies, an offshoot of the Special Olympics 
(started by Anthony's parents, Eunice and Sargent Shriver), which pairs 
mentally retarded youths with college students for group and one-on-one 
activities. 
</P>
<P>
So far chapters have started at Georgetown and Catholic universities, and now 
the 23-year-old Shriver has graduated from school and headed West to drum up 
grass-roots support in Los Angeles. A party at Santa Monica's Q gallery last 
week kicked off his efforts, and artist Nancy Frey donated all proceeds from 
sales of her paintings to Best Buddies. 
</P>
<P>
Frey, Shriver and friend Jimmy Shay organized the event, which drew Maria 
Shriver, Maryam D'Abo, Jacqueline Stallone (Sly's mom) and Bruce Jenner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Here, Frey, left, and Shriver discuss plans for the group. MIKE MEADOWS 
/ Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
