</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rebound in Foreign Stock Buying: American investors added $1.5 billion to their 
holdings of foreign stocks last year, reversing the net sales of 1987, the 
Securities Industry Assn. reported. In 1987, the year of the crash, Americans 
had sold $1.1 billion more of foreign stocks than they bought, the group said. 
Meanwhile, foreigners sold more U.S. stocks than they bought last year by a 
margin of $2.1 billion, compared to net purchases of $16.3 billion in 1987. 
Foreign investment in all kinds of U.S. securities rose to $75 billion last 
year from $69.4 billion in 1987, according to the survey, which covered 
investors in Britain, the United States, West Germany, Japan and Canada. 
</P>
