LOCAL; 
</P>
<P>
QUAKE JOLTS ORANGE, L.A. COUNTIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A mild earthquake early this morning was more of an annoyance than anything 
else to northern Orange County and Los Angeles County residents who were 
awakened at 5:44 a.m. by the temblor. 
</P>
<P>
Neither Orange nor Los Angeles County public safety officials reported any 
damage or injury from the quake, which seismologists at Caltech said registered 
a 2.9 in magnitude. It was centered beneath the Hacienda Heights area in Los 
Angeles County. 
</P>
<P>
The scientists said the shock was unrelated to the twin quakes in October, 
1987, which devastated nearby Whittier. Two other quakes shook the area over 
the weekend. A quake measuring 3.7 struck one mile northwest of Brea Saturday 
night, and seismologists reported a magnitude 3.4 quake centered 27 miles 
offshore from Oceanside on Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
