P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
ACCOUNTING OF B-2 PROGRAM URGED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The chairman of the House Armed Services Committee said today that recent data 
on the B-2 stealth bomber indicates that the cost of the program may have risen 
to about $75 billion. 
</P>
<P>
Rep. Les Aspin (D-Wis.) said the estimated cost may have risen by about $17 
billion over the last two years, and he urged Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to 
declassify as much information as possible on the program to build 
radar-evading bombers. 
</P>
<P>
"A straightforward accounting of the B-2's cost, schedule, capabilities and 
management would contribute to the program's creditability and accountability," 
Aspin said in a two-page letter to Cheney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
